These details must be carefully noted and borne in mind if we would duly appraise the intemal evidence of the verbal text'on which l shall have to dwell at some length in another chapter. But the very noting of them brings its own reward by casting a ray or two of light on the previous history of the contents of our sacramentary.

' lf the Corpus document be what 1 think it, it is either a copy of some earlier manuscript which comprised, like itself, the contents of St Augustine’s liber missalis and, intermingled with them, the accretions of

subsequent centuries, or it is a first coadunation of primitive and of adventitious elements. The former of these two hypotheses is the less probable; for it is not likely that in such earlier manuscript as it presupposes the anachrouous collocation we have noticed of the three messes on foll. 14 o. and 15 would have been allowed to remain un- rectified.
